{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_frenchbulldog_ver04/data/sn83045433/00280764140/1921012301/0336.xml":{"full_text":"ARGENTINA MAY\nPUT HEAVY TAX ON\nEXPORT WHEAT\nNfrth American Product\nLikely to Gain in Favor\nAs Result.\nr\nCHICAGO MART BUSY\nPortugal Now Seeking Huge\nStocks?Australian\nOutput Low.\nCHICAGO. Jan. 2S. Impending\nmovement of the Argentine crop\nhas'been a strong influence in the\nwharft market during the week.\nSelling of this crop has been delarid\nby failure of the Argentine\ngovernment to determine amount of\ntax.\" V any, upon exportation*. It\nla thought that the delay is due to\ncareful consideration of the financial\nneeds of Argentina. Vbose resources\nare said to be none too\nlarg?. With this thought in mind. It\nfallows that a rather liberal tax\nwill be Imposed, which, of course.\nwill be reflected in the asking price\naad. as matters now stand, result\nId a higher price for Argentine\nwheat, delivered in Europe, than for\nUnited States wheat.\nEuropean buying has been moderated\nslightly. Nevertheless better\nthan an average business is reported\nas cloaed each day.\nPortugal <s inquiring for some j\nBOO 6(J0 tons of foodstuffs, half of'\nwhich is wheat, a portion of it for\nimmediate shipment.\ncrop of India has been suffer-\ning from drought, but recent rains\nhave been beneficial.\nThs Australian crop is not affording\nas large a ?urplus as expected,\nestimates being reduced to abound\n18.006,000 bushels.\nThe state erf mind of the American\npublic is exhibited in the wheat\nraarltet by a practically complete\nabsefl<^e of investment or so-called\nspeculative demand. The lack of\nbuying of this character permits\npTicea to drag whenever the export\nbuy!nft ceases and affords an lllua- j\ntration of conditions which would j\nundoubtedly exist in case the sy.?tem\nof future trade were done away\nwith of hampered by restriction#.\nCoarse grains. particularly corn,\nare suffering from a very poor demand\nfrom Eastern and Southern]\nconsuming sections. In addition to\nthis the movement of corn from the\ncountry to terminal markets has!\nbeen toeavy. Under the combined\ninfluences of free movement and in-\nsufficient demand the enormous sur- I\nplus of foodstuffs has be*n brought\nto mind and prices have dropped\ncorrespondingly.\nDomestic trade in fresh meats has been*\nquite encouraging, and there\nhss been a small foreign demand for\nlard. European demand is expected,\nto improve. This feeling is born of\nthe improvement in the forelsrn ex- j\nchange market. There is also an\nexcellent shipping demand for hogs\nas well as from packing interests.\nCANADIAN MONEY\nDISCOUNT STARTS\n\nCleveland Bankers Put End to\n..Free Exchange at\nBig Loss.\nCLEVELAND. Ohio, Jan. 25.?\nCleveland bankers exploded a gold\nec fcutrble here by suddenly deciding\nto cJiarge a discount of 20 per cent\non all Canadian money.\nThey claim they have been playing?\nthe part of the \"golden fleece\"\nan<* that a host of Jasons have\nfleeced tnem of thousands of dollars.\nTjiere was no complicated \"Ponzi\nmefiod involved in profiting from\nthe* difference in the rate of exchange\nOn every investment of\n$8,900 a profit of 11.000 was made.\nThe! *8,950 in Anurican money was\nex^sanged in Canada for 810,000 in\nCanadian money. It was placed in\niirdulation here at face value.\nlinkers paid the tolls. They accepted\nCanadian money at par and\nin ilttpping it back to Canada lost\nthe\" oflterence in the rate of exchange.\nT&ey were content to stand the\nloss as long as it was comparatively\nsmall, but when their 'coffers\nwere flooded with many thousands\nof Canadian silver pieces, they\nstarted an investigation and found\nthat several crowds of men and\nwomen made a regular business of\nIt.\nThe gangs realized merchants\nand restaurant men and others\nwould balk at the paper, but would\nunhesitatingly accept silver. One\nman brought In silver by the trunk\nloa&r police found when they detained\na man and woman as suspicious\ncharacters. No arrests were\nmade as the transactions were held\nabsolutely legal.\nPHILADELPHIA PRODUCE.\ni\nPHILADELPHIA, Jan. 22.?Butter?Dull\nand nominal. The quotations;\nSolid-packed creamery, fancy,\nJitgh-scoring goods. 52Ha54Hc;\nextras. Sllic; extra firsts, 49 ^4a\n50^?fc; firsts. 42a48c; fancy, 53Ha\nSS^ie; fair to good, 42HaS2Hc;\nprints Jobbing at 61a63c for fancy\nand -48a60c for fair to choice.\nEfS*?Dull at late decline. Quotations:\nNearby firsts, 64c per doz.:\nnearby current receipts, 63c; Western\nextra firsts. 64c; do. firsts, 63c;\nInferior lots lower. Southern, 62c;\nttMft candled eggs jobbing at 77a\n78e: fair to ?ood, 69a76c.\nCheese?Firmly held. Quotations:\nSew Tork. whole milk, flats, fancy,\nhald. Ma!9c; do, fair to good, Held.\n26a27c: do, fancy, fresh. 25a25^c;\ndo. common to fair, fresh, 22a24c;\nLonghorns, held. 29c; do. fresh, 29c;\nsingle Daisies, held. 27a28c; do.\nfresh. 2SaJ7c: jobbing sales of fancy\nhold goods. 30a31c.\nLive poultry?Fowls, fancy, 34a\nJSc; exceptional lots higher; medium.\n3Sa33c: small and Interior, 29\na3?e; White Leghorn fowls, 32a33c;\nspring chickens, fancy, weighing\n1H and 2V4 lbs. and over apiece,\n3ia37e: young roosters, fancy, softmeatad.\n32a34c; staggy. yonng roosters.\niSa*8c: old roosters. 23aJ4c.\nTurkeys, fancy. 50a55c; do, ordinary,\n3Ja4?c Ducks, choice. 35a40c; do.\nMascoT). 28a30c. Geese, 2Sa32c.\nPigeons. per pair, 45aS0c.\nDrassed poultry?Turkeys, fancy,'\nVirginia and West Virginia, 58a?vc;\nWestern, dry-packed. 56aSSc; old\ntoms. 50c; fair to good, 40a45c:\nfowls In boxes, fresh-killed. 4V4 and\n5 lbs. and over apiece. 40c; weighing\n4 lbs.. 39c; weighing 3H lbs..\nItalic, watching 1 lbs., 30a33c;\nMETAL PRODUC'\nFAR ABOVE\nCoal and Petroleum\nGold D\n(By Tke Washington He\nWe pointed out recently in thi\nproduction for 1920 amounted to\ngreatest ever recorded for this com\nigw was nearly 30 per cent great\nproduction of important commoditi\ngeneral condition of the country,\nproduction data 