ction with these comn\nproduction of both gold and silvei\ncompared with earlier years. Pre\nfor the 1920 production in the mi\ngiven below include more than 95 p\nI exclusive of Alaska and the Phili]\nI gold has remained constant, the ou\nI proportionate to the quantity prod\nPRODUCTION OF GOLD A\nSTA\nYear.\n1913 $7\n191 8 5\n191 9 4\n192 0 3\nGold production in 1920 of less\nthan in 1913 and 18 per cent less tl\nlow record. The output of silver 1\nthat in 1919, but 20 per cent bclov\n(Copyright, 1921. by Tt\nDEPRESSION SEEN\nIN COTTON SALES\nSelling Continues on Free\nScale But Avoids Lowest\nLevels.\nNEW YORK. Jan. 22.?Selling of\ncotton on a free scale was continued\ntoday and the market was again\ndepressed. Although it finished\nabove the lowest, renewed liquidation\nof March and straddle reversing\nwere the features of the session.\nSpot firms were again conspicuous\nby their selling of the March position.\nat times buying May against\ntheir sales of the nearer montn.\nWall street houses also sold, probably\ninfluenced by weakness in securities.\nInitial quotations showed losses,\nof 2 to 22 points under local, South,\nLiverpool and Wall street selling.\nRight after the call the decline was\nincreased, but a demand from shorts\neffected a temporary rally. The upturn\nmet increased offerings and the\nheavy pressure against March had\nan unsettling effect on sentiment\ngenerally. Before the end of the\nfirst hour prices dropped into new\nlow ground for the present movement\ndownward. March fell to 14.25,\ncompared with 16.60, the high level\ntouched on the Tally last week,\nwhile the decide carried May off\nto 14.92, contrasted with 16.53, the\nrecent high mark\nAccording to estimates on the\nfloor, selling of March* by several\nbrokers, believed to be acting for\none important flrm, aggregated\nclose to 75,000 bales in the last few\ndays. Traders found nothing in the\nnews to indicate any change in\nbusiness conditions abroad.\nWeek-end covering caused ?rn improvement\nfrom the lowest in the\nfinal dealings, although last quotations\nstill showed net losses of\n.25 to 48 points.\nSpot here was quiet, with middling\n50 points lower at 16.15c.\nThere were no sales.\nSpot at New Orleans was quiet,\nwith the revised quotation of middling\nfixed at 14.50c. There were\nno sales.\nReceipts of cotton in bales at important\npoints today were: Galveston,\n7,647; New Orleans, 3,500;\nSavannah, 1,141; Augusta, 1,175;\nHouston. 8,211.\nFollowing are today's quotations:\nCc t ton? Open. High. Low. Close.\nJanuary 16.30 16.80 15.00 15.93\nMarch 14 46 14.09 14.25 14.46\nMay 14.73 14.75 14.43 14.00\nJuly 14.94 14.94 14.64 14.70\n(Quotations furnlahad by W- B. Hibbs\nCo., Members Hew Tork Cotton Exchange.)\nfowls, fresh-killea, in bbls., arypicked,\nweighing 4 and 5 lbs. apiece,\n39c; weighing 3H lbs.. 31a34c;\nweighing 3 lbs. and under, 30a32c;\nroasting chickens, Western, drypacked,\nin boxes, weighing 4H and\n*5 lb. and over apiece, 38a39c; do,\nweighing 4 lbs., 36a37c; do. in bbls.,\nweighing 4 and 5 lbs. and over\napiece, 35a37c; fryers, Western,\nweighing 3 and 3 Mi lbs. apiece, 33a\n35c; broilers, Western, dry-picked,\nHON IN 1920\nPREVIOUS YEAR\n\nYield AUo Increases,\neel in e*.\nraid's Keonomlc Expert.)\ns column that the total agricultural\nmore than 300.000,000 tons, or the\nntry. The total [farm production in\ner than itf 1913' Figures on total\nies form an excellent index of the\nIt is particularly difficult to obtain\nommodities except at the five-year\nManufactures. The Geological Siirrvals\nauthoritative figures on the\nnd certain reliable trade information\nn issued on the 1920 production of\nse figures reduced to short tons in\nseveral recent years and for 19* 3iron\nare for pig iron manufactured,\neum production is partly estimated\nOF MINERALS.\nl?i?n 1918 nio \"WO\n1.253.321 43.738,733 34.737.208 41.180.G00\n948 nflO 904.287 643.000 617.R0G\n584.587 492.405 452.272 <<0.000\n548,450 538,905 424,433 474.000\ni.829.680