Grain prices\nclosed with substantial gains on\nthe Board of Trade today. Wheat\nwas the leader. Other grains followed\nin the upward trend.\nWheat prices were Influenced by\nunfavorable crop reports. The Oklahoma\nState Commissioner of AgriI\nculture reported the green bug and\nI Hessian fly. From the iddle West\nwinter wheat belt came reports of\nI alternate freezing and thawing and\nI lack of snow to protect the crop.\nVolume of trade was not large, but\nwhat the market lacked in activity\nwas made up in strength. Exporters\nwere in the market and EastI\nern interests bought freely on soft\nspots. Announcement of a $30,000,I\n000 loan to Belgium was a strengthening\nfactor. The market closed at\ni an advance of 2% to 3 cents.\nCorn was firm and commission\nI house buying^ was active throughout\nthe session, although no large\namounts were taken. Selling pressure'\ndeveloped on the advance. Domestic\ndemand for corn wag slow\nand export demand was light, owing\nto Inability of shippers to offer\ncorn for immediate delivery. The\nmarket closed at an advance of\nto cent.\nI Trade in oats was of good volI\nume. Commission house interests\nwere In the market. Selling pressure\ndeveloped on advances, a good\npart of It being in the way of realising.\nThe market closed at an ad|\nvance dt to cent.\nBarl6y was unchanged to 1 cent\n[higher and rye was cent lower.\nShoft interests were on the buyI\ning side in the provision market.\nI At the close prices generally were\nhigher.\nFollowing ?r? today's quotations:\nWheat? Open. High. Low. Close.\nMarch 1.64% 1.67% 164% 1*7%\nj May 1 56 1.58% 1.54 1.58*\nI Corn?\ni May 67% .68% .67% .68%\nJuly 68% .60% .68% .60%\nOate?\nMay 43% .44% .43% .44%\nJuly 41 .44% .43% .44%\nPork?\nJunuary 23.50\nMapr\nLard?\nM l^lta 1870 18 90 1881 1877\nMay .12.65 12.72 12.62 12.72\n(Quotations furnished by W. B. Hibbs\nCo., Memmbers Chicago Board of Trade.)\n.weighing 1% and 2 lbs. apiece, 43a\n45c; broilers, nearby, weighing 1%\nand 2 lbs. apiece, 46a48c; roasting\nchickens, nearby, weighing 4 and 5\nlbs. apiece. 32a40c; frying chickens,\nnearby, weighing 3 and lbs.\n[apiece, 34a36c; old roosters, dry-I\npicked, 28c; ducks, Western, fancy,\n37a40c; geese, .Western, 30a32c;\nguineas, Rfj- pair, spring, flal.25;\nold, 7Sa85c.* j\nVETERAN BUSIN\nHEADS L<\n2|\nM ?i\ni Bl\nHHA\nALBERT SC\nManager of the Connecticut-Cop\ncently elected president of the Wa\nSchulteis has been prominent\nand has a number of important b\nas first vice president of the Chan\nwas elected to head this active 01\nGOODS, NOT GOLD,\nI TO TRIM HUGE\nEUROPEAN DEBT\nChase National Bank Ofj\nficial Declares High\nTariffs Absurd.\n'OPPOSES CHANGES\nI A. Barton Hepburn Says He\nSees No Need for Tariff\nReadjustment.\n\n\"There is only one way in which I\nEurope can ever hope to pay the\nUnited States the billions of dollars\nthey owe us and that is by sending\nus goods.v She cannot send, much j\nmore gold. The only way in which j\nshe can hope to pay off this lebt, or\neven to pay interest on it. is by\nsending goods to us. nelMng them\nin crtir markets and leaving the\nmoney with us.\"\nThis is the keynote of an interview\nwith A. Barton Hepburn, chair\nman of the advisory board of the\nChase National Bank. New York\nI City, and made public yesterday.\nThe interview follows:\n\"I am~~concerned here with the\nproblem of Protective Tariff vs.\nRevenue Tariff under normal conditions.\nA life-long Republican. 1\ncould offer strong arguments for\nprotective tariffs under conditions\nto which we were accustomed in the\ndays before the war. But the present\nsituation makes the old arguments\nwholly in applicable. We are\nfaced by the fact that Europe owes\nus many billions of dollars, which\nshe can only pay by shipping goods\nto us. European governments fewe\nour own government approximately\n$10,000,000,000. In addition to that\nEurope owes private investors in\nI the United States $1,500,000,000 to\n$2,000,000,000 in bonds. Over and\nabove that. Europe owes private\nJcreuitors in the United States, in\nthe form of an unfunded or floating 1\ndebt, a sum approaching, if it does\nnot exceed, $4,000,000,000, making a\ntotal debt of JCurope to the Unitell\nStates of not less than $15,500,000.000.\nof which an appallingly large\nproportion is in unfunded form.\nCan't Send (>old.\n\"I repeat that the only way in\nwhich Europe can ever hope to\npay any considerable part of this\ndebt is by sending us goods. She\ncannot send\"mueh more gold. The\ncreation of our great merchant marine\nand the expansion of our\nAmerican banking activities have\nlessened America's dependance on\nEurope for shipping and banking\nservices, and, at the present moment,\nthe actual balance of payments\non shipping is against Europe,\nrather than in her favor. The\nonly way in which she can hope to\npay off this debt, or even to pay\ninterest on it. is. by sending goods\nto u8, selling them in our markets,\nand leaving the money with us.\n\"It needs little argument to show\ntha thigh protective tariffs interfere\nwith the importation of manufactured\ngoods from Europe, greatly\nincrease Europe's difficulties in\nmeeting her obligations to us, and\ngreatly lessen the prospects of our\nreceiving payments from her. It is\na policy which is financially suicidal\nif rigorously carried out. I\nam, therefore, vigorously opposed\nto an upward readjustment of our\ntariffs at the present time. I call\nattention to the fact that the platform\nof the Republican party promulgated\nat Chicago last summer\ntook cognizance of this exceptional\nsituation and refrained. In view of\nthis situation, from making aay\ndefinite commitment of ifie party\nto an early general it^reasc of tariff\nrates. The piriform said. The\nuncertain and unsettled conditions\nof international balances, the abnormal\neconomic and trade situation\nof the. world, and the impossibility\nof forecasting accurately\neven the near future preclude the\nformulation of a definite program\nto meet conditions a year hence.'\nOppone Tariff Revision.\n\"I do not question that particular\nschedules may need ipodiflcatlon in\nthe light of the developments since\nthe last tariff law was passed. Some\nschedules, by being revised upward,\ncan be made mdre productive of\nrevenue without hampering the imports\nfrom Europe. Other schedules\nmay made mpre productive of\nrevenue by beirfg lowered in such\na way as to\" permit the freer entry\nof certain goods, with the consequent\nincrease in the volume ol\ness man\nx:al chamber\nbH?\n\nPSv^J\n^kVat\nHULTEIS,\nperthite Pie Company, and reshington\nChamber of Commerce,\nin local affairs for many ytars\nmsiness connections. He served\niber for several- terms before he\nrganization.\nMARSH URGES\nQUICK REPEAL\nOF RAILROAD BILL\nFarmers' Representative\nSays Cummins Bill Is\nCause of Depression.\nFAVORS WAR STATUS\nTestifies Before Senate Committee\non Amendment to\nAntitrust Act.\nThe Cwmmins-Esch transposition\nact was described as one of\nthe main causes of the present financial\ndepression by Denjamin C.\nMarsh, of the Farmers* National\nCouncil, before the Senate Interstate\nCommerce Committee yester-1\nday.\nHis testimony was taken when the\ncommittee resumed hearings on the\nproposed amendment to the Clayton\nantitrust act which would prohibit\ninterlocking directorates between\nrailroads and supply companies.\n\"In order to restore the confidence\nof the American people and to reestablish\nagriculture, as well as\nother business and commerce. Congress\nmust, instead of tinkering\nwith the Interstate Commerce act.\npromptly restore the railroads to\nunified gevernment operation under\ncontrol similar to that authorized In\nthe Federal control act.\" Marsh said.\n\"The Cummins-Ksch law is one of\nthe most serious causes of our\npresent financial depression and of\nfarmers' troubles. Instead of onsidering\nmethods to enable the responsible\ndirectors, or officers, of\nhe railroads further to exploit the\npublic through interlocking direc-\ntorates in financial and commercial\nconcerns. Congress has a solemn\nduty to repeal the Cummlns-Esch\nlaw and restore the war status of\nthe railroads. reducing railroad\nrates to those in effect when the\nroads were returned and providing\nif there be any deficit. It should be\npaid by taxation.\"\nInflux of Buyers\nCheer8 Merchants\nNEW YORK. Jan. 22.?There was\nconsiderable jubilation in merchandising\ncircles here at the closing of\nlast week, due to a large influx of\nbuyers from the West. A jrreat\nmany jobbers in an exuberance of\nspirits raised prices from 5 to 25\nper cent when they saw the numbet\nof visitors. The natural effect was\nshown in sales of only a fractional\npart of the orders, which buyers\nhad intended to leave here. One or\ntwo of the mercantile bankers became\ncognisant of this situation\nthis morning and there were some\nrather peremptory orders issued,\nvviiich in these individual cases resulted\nin bringing prices back to\nthe level of a week ago.\ngoods on which the tariff is collected.\nA strong case can be made\non the basis of military considerations\nfor special treatment of dyestuffs.\nparticularly If world conditions\nare to remain so disturbed\nthat the possibility of*another war\nis seriously to be entertained. But\na general revision upward of the\ntariff would be an inexcusable blunder\nin the present situation.\n'The proposed high tariffs on\nwheat and other farm products of\nwhich we are large exporters must\nbe reckoned as absurd from another\npoint of view. Tariffs on competi-^\ntively produced articles of export\ndo not in general, affect prices.\nWe might Impose a tariff of $1 a\npound on cottoA for the purpose of\nshowing the folly of a tariff of\nthis kind. Such a tariff would\nprobably have no effect at all upon\nthe general price of cotton, though\nit would, of course, have disastrous\neffects upon industries in the United\nStates employing certain kinds of\ncotton which we do not produce at\nhome. It is well not to trifle with\nthe farmers in thir manner, and\nbelievers in the long-run policy of\nprotective tariffs, who look forward\nto re-establishing the protective\nsystem after the present abnormalities\nin international trade relations\nhave been straightened out.\nwill do well not to irritate the\nfarmers at the present time by giving\nthem a Dead Sea apple, which\nturns to ashes on \"the lips.\"\nSEE GRAIN STAB1\nTO FARMERS'\n\nBache Review Predict* I\nWholesale Pricei\nNEW YORK. Jan. 21. \"Th* j\nfarmer is receiving wide attention\nIn the journals throughout t be\ncountry because of hid important\nposition in the q^mmunlty. and be-\ncause, having raised a record crop\n(deflation in the meantime having\nset in), he is unable to obtain a?\nmuch for his good* as it cost him\nto produce them,\" says this week's\nBache Review.\n\"Grain values have been stabilised\nsomewhat since the farmer's\nresistance to low prices began. The\nmilling trade, which has been -operating\nat 36 to $0 per cent of the\ncapacity during nearty* all of the\nlast six months of tt>e year, shows\nsome improvement, but nothing like\nnormal as yet. It is estimated Chat\nour domestic mills consumed 70,000,006\nbushels less wheat up to\nJanuary 1 compared with same period\na year ago. Flour stocks were\ncut down to very low level! with\nmany large consumers and dlstrin- i\nuter^ and there has been, since the\nfirst of the year, some disposition\nto take on moderate quantities.\n\"Many hold the opinion that it\nIs useless to expect prosperity I\nthroughout the country while price*\nfor grains are low, and that the\nplight of the agricultural commu- J\nnity. having limited buying power.\nmust have an effect on the trade of\nmanufacturing interests as long as\nlow values for the farmer's products\nprevail.\n\"Some of the farmers Whq sola\ntheir wh?at at low prices are aaid i\nto have bought futures believing tn j\nhigher prices, and 'are trying to]\nmake up for the ^ifferenc* in the-j\nprice a* which they sold their grain. 1\nand their belief in its actual worth.'I\n\"Farmers who sold their crops j\nand were far-seeing enough to j\nhedge by sales of futures in Sep- j\ntember and October, have secured\ngood profits provided they have covered.\nbut it. is. questionable wheth< r\nmany farmers understand hedging- j\nHowever, our Chicago correspondent\nadvises us that many farmers!\nin the Northwest do hedge. Others\nIn scattered localities sell their\ngrain and buy futures if they are\nbullish. thus avoiding carrying\ncharges. As a usual practice, how- j\never, the hedging operations commence\nafter the grain has been sold\nby the farmer, beginning with the\ncountry elevators.\n\"The month has proceeded with a\nremarkable absence of distubance. 1\nsuch as was expected from a large\nrecord of failures which did not I\nTRADE BOARD D\nIN SHOWER OF\nFROM GIRLS\nCONTINUED FROM TACK ONE\nfervor provoked the members of the j\nboard to prolonged applause.\nAnother stunt which made a de- i\ncld'd hit was a dance by Miss Little I\non a huge platter which was held\nup by a dozen volunteer members.\nHave A\"t.\nAnother act which was repeatedly i\nencored was \"Skipping Through the\nI Meadows.\" Six girls, led by Miss\nMurray, and) equipped with electrically\nlighted jumping ropes, partici-:\nI pated. They were: Misses Ida B.lt.1\nLouis Belt. Mildred McLeod. Marion\nO'Connor. Loretta Bradley and Mildred\nInge.\npertiaps the distinguished gather\nin8 was most amused by a motion\npicture made for the occasion. whWh\nhad in its cast a number of prom Lent\nmember, of the board This\npicture, through trick photography,\n'made Fifteenth street and Pennsyl!\nvanla avenue resemble Broadway at\nits busiest Intersection, much to the\nmerriment of all present. It also\ncontained graphic arguments wh>\nthe District should be given natlon.il\nrepresentation.\nlocal Mra\nBut. perhaps, what pleased the\nmost was the Part which depicted\nWaters being arrested while speed- i\nIng with his talent and William F\nHam driving a horse car on What\nthey termed the \"Ham and Kg*'\nI line.\nA couple of pleasing number*\nwere contributed by the Washington\nquartet, which Is composed of\nthe following: Mrs. Mary Sherler\nBowie. Miss Richie McLain. J. F M\nBowie and Fred East. The quartet\nalso accompanied Mrs. Jiaycock in a\nseries of old folk songs.\n0*CMB?r Slag*.\nAn entertainment of any proportions\nwould seem incomplete if j\nGeorge O'Connor were not inoJuded\non the program, and tor this reason\nthe farseeing Waters persuaded him\nto sing several songs In his inimitable\nfashion.\nGeorge always tries to he immune\nfrom encores, but when the n>em;\nbers even went so far as to beat\non their pKates-with their silverware\nhe was forced to succumb to their\nwishes and \"kick in\" one more number.\nOrekestra Please*.\nOrchestra! numbers were supplied\nunder the direction of Sol Minster,\nwhile George Wilson and Mat Horn\npresided at the piano.\nAt the suggestion of ThoV,a*\nBradley, president of the board, a\nrising vote of thanks was Riven to\nWaters, who has worked tireles?i>\nIn the interest of the midwinter\ndinner for the past several montM.\nFollowing are the names of the\nmembers of the board and the r\nguests who were present at tne\ndinner:\nChas. J. Columbus. Ernest 8.\nn. Neumeyer. Jr.. Frank H. Metre. B?U??\nPerry. Lee L. Heirsll. frank 1 K', t\nK. C. Cummlnga. T. W. Oaddlrk, M. T\nFlnaan. E K, Port. w\nLambert, Darid J. Howell. rh\" *Omm.\nT M Flmpte. George-M.\nL. R Lipscomb. Charles 8. KJ,'K.\nBwaa. II W. Ireland, H. F Mmbsll.\nRichard K Harris. Howard Moras. C. H.\nI Leavell. K. J. I-onry. O. M. Thoraa> J\nJohnson. Ran, Ed moo.ton Berrer^JR\nBtrlntfellew. W F Kelly. H A. Rewu\nL O. Rena. W. C. Toat. Dr.\nYates. H. >1 Roe?r. E F. Gee. Pr E\nSi. Gustafson, T. W Green\nDeyber. F. R Weller. K. L ?mlth_ Staa\nley T MllUkea. C. C. McDerltr L\nPriace. Thomas P. Brown. Patar M .B\"**Frank\nMitchell. Harry Allen. H. C. Stewart,\nJacob Pyra